This feels like tying a few things together: batching the future creation, executing the batches one after another, and collecting the results.

I'd have expected something like:

```reason

/* this is the part where I prepare my data for the concurrent execution */
module type List = {
  /* take a list of 'a, and an int for how many to put in each bucket */
  let chunks_of: (int, list('a)) => list(list('a));
};

let futures = [1, 2, 3, 4] |. List.map(x => () => Future.value(x)); /* this could also be lazy futures */
let maxConcurrency = 2;
let chunks: list(list(unit => Future.t(int)) = List.chunks_of(maxConcurrency, futures);
/* [ [() => Future(1), () => Future(2)], [() => Future(3), () => Future(4)] ] */

/* this is the part where I build up the computation */
module type Future = {
  let all: (list(t('a)), list('a) => 'b); /* from https://github.com/RationalJS/future/issues/16 */
};

let sequence: list(list(unit => Future.t('a))) => Future.t(list(list('a)) = chunks => {
  let rec consumer = (cs, acc) => {
    switch (cs) {
    | [] => Future.value(acc);
    | [h, ...t] => {
        /* initialize all futures in this chunk: this would be more elegant using Lazy/Force */
       Future.all(List.map(x => x(), h))
       |. Future.flatMap(results => consumer(t, [results, ...acc])))
      }
    }
  };
  consumer(chunks, []);
};

/* this is the part where you consume it */
later_values.get( values => Js.log(values) );
```

Of course this is just a sketch but it's a bit more elegant, it (from what I can see) won't throw any exceptions anywhere, it can still be optimized with mutable cursors and good ol' `while` loops if the performance needs it.

Just a thought! Good work @dvisztempacct on pushing for concurrency idioms in the library 🙌

An even smaller example we could use here that I think would cement the intuition that polyvars are closer to the data itself than to defined types would be a list:

```ocaml
# let my_favorite_fruits = [ `banana ];;
val my_favorite_fruits : [> `banana ] list

# let my_favorite_fruits = [ `banana; `apple ];;
val my_favorite_fruits : [> `apple | `banana ] list

# let my_favorite_fruits = [ `banana; `apple; `kiwi ];;
val my_favorite_fruits : [> `apple | `banana | `kiwi ] list
```

